post_text:
What a week at Richmond High School! Thank you to everyone who had a hand in welcoming all of our students back. Thank you to the parents who have been patient and understanding with us as we work through the changes. Thank you to our fantastic staff for giving 110% to make everyone feel welcome, our custodial and support staff for keeping our building sanitized, and most importantly, our student body. These incredible kids have adapted to the many changes we have put in place and done it with a smile on their faces. (We think, it’s hard to tell under the masks) We look forward to another great week.

Good things are happening at Richmond Community Schools...let's keep it going!

More and more families are choosing Richmond each day that the District has added a 5th section of Kindergarten, a 5th section of 1st Grade, a 5th section of 3rd Grade, and additional sections of Government/Economics, English 9, English 11, and Geometry.

Finally, over 225 students have signed up for the virtual learning option.

It's a great day to be a Blue Devil!

Lunch Aides

The purpose of these positons is to assist students in the lunch room, lunchroom cleaning, lunchroom and playground supervision, and other duties assigned by the building principal to support the District’s COVID-19 Preparedness and Response Plan. The positions are at-will employees.

$10.61 per hour.

Elementary School: 10:15 AM to 1:00 PM (2.75 hours/day) on Full days of School. Position does not report on half days. Hours may be adjusted to meet the needs of the building.

Middle School: 10:15 AM to 1:15 PM (3.0 hours/day) on Full days of School. Position does not report on half days. Hours may be adjusted to meet the needs of the building.

post_text:
COVID-19 Building Aides

The purpose of these positions is to assist with health screening and temperature checks, disinfecting and cleaning common areas throughout the building, monitoring movement of students, and other duties assigned by the building principal to support the District’s COVID-19 Preparedness and Response Plan. The positions are at-will employees and are considered temporary positions.

$10.61 per hour.

Elementary School (2 positions). 7:40 AM to 2:10 PM on Full Days of School and 7:40 AM to 10:40 AM on Half Days of School. Hours may be adjusted to meet building needs.

Virtual Parent Meeting #5

Join Superintendent Walmsley as he holds the fifth parent meeting discussing Richmond's Return to School: COVID-19 Preparedness and Response Plan. Details of the required components of the Return to School plan will be discussed as well as an overview of the in-person and virtual options for families. The Return to School: COVID-19 Preparedness and Response Plan is being presented to the Board of Education for approval on Monday, August 10, 2020.

The parent meeting will take place on Tuesday, August 11, 2020 at 9:00am via ZOOM. To participate, visit the district's website for Zoom log-in and password information.

Previously Parent meeting sheld, July 27th at 9:00am, July 27th at 2:00pm, July 27th at 7:00pm, and August 8th at 10:00am.

ATTENTION RICHMOND HIGH SCHOOL; FALL STUDENT-ATHLETES: You MUST have a MHSAA Athletic Questionnaire (ONLY if you had a physical during the 2019-2020 school year) or a MHSAA Physical Form (completed by a physician) AND a COMPLETED Athletic Registration on FamilyID to participate next week. Links can be found under the “Athletic Participation Information” heading on the district website: http://richmond.ss7.sharpschool.com/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1271767&pageId=3513629

The start dates, times and locations are as follows:
Volleyball: August 12, 4PM (JV Baseball Field)
Boys Soccer: August 12, 4PM (Behind MS Playground)
Cross Country: August 12, 10AM (Meet at Softball Concessions)
Football: August 10, 3PM (Behind RMS)
Boys Tennis: August 12, 6PM (Bailey Park Tennis Courts)
Sideline Cheer: August 11, 9AM (AYSO Field)
Girls Golf: TBD

More information was sent via email on August 3. Contact Chris Rinehart (crinehart@richmond.k12.mi.us) if you have any questions. #GoBlueDevils

post_text:
Dear Will L. Lee Families:

We would like to invite you to attend a Lee School Parade on June 23rd at 6:30 p.m. Usually on the last day of school, our staff stands near the bus loop to wave goodbye to the students and wish them a great summer. This year, as you know, we were unable to do this yearly tradition. We have decided to do a Lee School Parade with families riding in their vehicles and the staff standing near the bus loop waving to students as they are driven through the bus loop.

In order to make this a successful event for all those involved, we ASK THAT ALL FAMILIES STAY IN THEIR VEHICLES during the entire parade. Staff will be smiling and waving and wishing all our students…

As of today, the State has NOT provided clear direction to schools on whether or not they will reopen, as we traditionally know them, in the Fall of 2020.

While there has been much discussions around schools opening, there is equally as many unanswered questions that the State has yet to formulate answers. Richmond Community Schools is interested in gathering your perspective on several issues that may potential affect your child's education and instruction provided by Richmond Community Schools in the Fall.

Parents of Richmond school-age children, please go to the District's website (www.richmond.k12.mi.us) to complete the "Return to School Parent/Guardian Survey." Your perspective is important and valued as we plan for the fall.

Richmond Middle School teachers and administrators made special deliveries to our Alice East Award winners this week. Each recipient is awarded a medal and certificate.

The Alice East award is an outstanding student and citizen award.

Background:
Alice East taught in the Richmond area for over forty years. During this time, she taught mostly in the one-room schools and worked almost entirely with Middle School age students. During the time she was teaching, she received many honors for her work with young people. Included in her awards were the Valley Forge Liberty Bell Award and the Little Red Schoolhouse Award, given to her by President Eisenhower for outstanding teaching.

This award…

Hello Parents,

RMS will be collecting school laptops and materials next week by grade levels at the dates and times listed below. post_text: This week students in Mrs. Hunter's 2nd grade class participated in “camping week”. Last week they received a package with all of the materials for this week. Students read about woodland animals, teepees, dream catchers, and friendship. Each reading correlated with a craft. They explored using compasses while practicing cardinal directions, creating a poem based on friendship, and used mini flashlights to read in the dark. For this weeks Zoom meetings students listened to new class books, and shared their “camping sites” (homemade tents). Great job this week!

For this weeks Zoom meetings students listened to new class books, and shared their “camping sites” (homemade tents). Great job this week!

post_text:
During the week of May 11th, Mrs. Gibson's kindergarten class worked on using transition words to retell the story "Little Penguin Gets the Hiccups." We also researched different animals and wrote down 3 important facts about the animal they chose. The students watched "fireworks" in a jar during a science experiment showing how different liquids react when poured together. We read our weekly paper book, practiced new sight words, explored the -ug word family, and practiced using ten frames. Our Friday activity was going on a house hunt to find objects that started with each letter of the alphabet. Another fun-filled week of learning!!
Mrs. Gibson's class webpage: https://gibsonsgroup.weebly.com/

post_text: Students in Mrs. Hunter's 2nd grade class have continued to work hard and share pictures of their work! Students worked on math word problems, reading comprehension, subtracting across zeros, and writing “would you rather” paragraphs. This weeks Class Dojo videos were math games/challenges. Race to a dollar is a game to practice adding coins with different values and trading in coins. Roll it, Tell it, Cover it is a game that students practice recognizing the time on both analog and digital clocks. Students have continued participating in Zoom meetings where they all get the chance to share something. post_text: This week Mrs. Gibson's kindergarten class worked extra hard on 5 star sentences! In order to have a 5 star sentence, we must check to make sure we have a capital at the beginning, finger spaces between words, punctuation at the end, sight words, and stretching out unknown words. We used our focus words for the week (have, help) in our sentences and we also wrote sentences about flowers! The students also made their own flower and labeled the parts of the flower. We worked on the -et word family, graphing flowers and bugs in math, and picked a community worker that we would like to be! We also held a Zoom show and tell and sang happy birthday to one of our classmates! It was another busy week full of learning! The students are doing awesome! Keep up the great work! Mrs. Gibson would like to thank all of the parents for the at-home support! You are all doing a great job...it definitely shows in the work that is turned in. Keep up the great work!

While the last couple of weeks have been unprecedented and historic, it has also been a time of inspiration and hope. Mrs. Jahr's 8th grade Social Studies students held a lively debate online this Wednesday on whether or not the current stay at home order violates constitutional rights. Students not only expressed their opinions, but conducted research into other historical events, such as when Lincoln suspended habeas corpus during the Civil War, and used facts to back their opinions. Great job, everyone!
>>>>>>> master

Next week, the students will debate about the second amendment.

post_text: This week students continued to work on learning packets as well as Class Dojo videos. Our class has weekly Zoom meetings to do a show and tell just like we would if we were in class. We also catch up with each other and go over class work for the week. Some students are learning about life cycles with caterpillars and are sharing what they learn with their friends on Zoom meetings. The Class Dojo challenges this week are playing a fraction game (writing fractions and creating them with shapes) and creating a poster to present facts about an animal (using text features). Keep up the great work Mrs. Hunter’s 2nd grade class!

post_text: This past week, students in Mrs. VanSledright's 1st grade class were reading stories provided to them along with stories of their choice to dig deeper and pull out specific information from those stories. They also worked on counting by groups of tens and adding tens to a 2-digit number. And many of them joined in on Zoom meetings to listen to stories, draw, and hunt for items around their homes. They have been working so hard!

post_text: Students in Mrs. Ranger’s 1st grade class viewed the story Flat Stanley on a you-tube read aloud. On Monday Flat Mrs. Ranger arrived in the student's mail. The adventures have begun...Ryder is reading with Mrs. Ranger listening on his shoulder. Eddie was so excited when he opened the mail he sat holding Mrs. Ranger's hand. Jett and Navi took Mrs. Ranger to pick up their Kroger Clicklist. Beverly and Payton work hard every day on their math and language arts assignments. Stella created her house map for social studies. A live science experiment is observed each week on Zoom, students were able to witness a chemical reaction when baking soda and vinegar mixed, causing a rubber glove to first inflate and then explode. The students also saw force and motion and observed a plate in motion and an egg at rest, resulting in the egg dropping straight down into a glass of water. The journey and adventures will continue this week as the students take Mrs. Ranger with them on their escapades.

post_text: April 28th was “pay it forward day” and in Mrs. Laura Ottenbacher’s GSRP preschool she encouraged her class to come up with a way to spread kindness and Carter Swartz and his family did just that! He decided they should write a letter like they did for their mail lady but for the waste management guys this time! He planned a treasure map, added some stickers and his mom Trisha put some money in a card. They finished their plan with Carter’s suggestion to tape the card to the garbage can so they could see it. 💙 Way to go, Carter! We are so proud of you!

post_text: This week students in Mrs. Hunter's 2nd grade class have been busy working on various activities. Some students have done the Class Dojo videos while others completed a “roll a story” activity. This weeks Class Dojo videos were on figurative language (taking a picture and creating own figurative language statements) and working with arrays (a game called “Array Capture”.) Many students spent the first few days doing their work outside and enjoying the beautiful weather! Students also finished up another Math Mystery using their math skills to crack the case. Students have continued to amaze me with all their hours work!

post_text: We had a busy weekin Mrs. Gibson's kindergarten class! The students worked extra hard this week on reading and reviewing sight words. The students worked on a 5-finger retell for the book "Bear's New Friend." They were able to identify the characters in the story, the setting, the beginning, middle, and end! We also worked on 3D shapes and went on a scavenger hunt around our homes to find objects that were 3D. The students recorded their findings on an activity page. On Wednesday, the students read a book three times through after first highlighting all the sight words in the book. They read the book first to themselves, then to an adult, then to a pet or stuffed animal! They are now… More

post_text: The GSRP preschoolers in Mrs. Laura Ottenbacher and Mrs. Labish’s class have been busy this past week! During their weekly zoom meeting, they each brought a recyclable item to the meeting to measure and discussed how to take care of the Earth. Mrs. O them read I Love the Earth. She encouraged them to make art or reuse their item for something else and get outside in their yard to look for ways to clean up the Earth! They picked up their preschool at home learning goodie bag and ended the week with Mrs. Mangune reading I Love As Much for letter “I” day. Way to go, Blue Devil Preschoolers!

Pictures, Pictures, Pictures

Once Kaiser studios re-opens they will begin processing the fun day pictures that were taken at the schools just prior to closing. They will then be printing those and mailing those pictures to parent homes.

The graduate composite is ready to print once they return. Kaiser is still accepting online orders for those. Parents can use this direct link for Will L Lee: https://orders.kaiserstudio.com/default.aspx?code=GRLEE
If you do not know if you ordered, please email cs@kaiserstudio.com and Kaiser can check for them before they place an online order. The link is available until May 1st . The graduate composites will be shipped to the school for distribution to the students.

post_text: This week, in Mrs. Hunter's 2nd grade class, there were two Class Dojo challenges- creating 2D and 3D shapes and making a fraction pizza. In honor of Earth Day students practiced labeling the Earth by doing their own research using a book on Epic. The read about the seven continents and were given a scavenger hunt for outside. Students practiced using text evidence through color coordinating their work as well as practicing finding parts of speech within sentences. I am so impressed with their hard work and all the videos/work they have been sending to me!

post_text:
Mrs. Goddard's remote learning classroom: Where every day is pajama day and every day is a learning day!! My wonderful, hardworking students have been sharpening their saw and keeping up on their 2nd grade skills at home. During our Zoom meeting last Friday, learning packets showed up in the mail and almost immediately I started receiving pictures of students working through them!! I was also impressed to see the pictures of hands-on learning taking place like counting real money and practicing spelling words by building words with letter tiles or legos.

Many have taken ownership of their learning by designing their own creative and challenging activities and taking learning to new…

post_text: Students in Mrs. Kania's 1st grade class have been working hard these last couple of weeks. We've practiced sight words and math facts. We have learned new things and practiced reading on Raz-Kids. We took a virtual field trip to the San Diego Zoo and wrote about what we learned. We've written about facts and opinions on spring, explored nature, participated in science experiments, decorated our windows for Rainbows over Michigan and even helped cook at home! Keep up the amazing work room 307! I am so very proud of you! Love, Mrs. Kania

post_text: Last week Mrs. Gibson's kindergarten students worked on retelling stories, using toys to make a graph, writing a "how to" paper, sorting and counting coins. On Friday, they did a Zoom science experiment. They put one egg in vinegar and one in water to compare what happens to each egg. They will report their findings on Monday by doing another Zoom session! It was a great week!

post_text: Attention Richmond community members, as you know many of our students' families are struggling financially in these difficult times. There are a number of seniors that are not able to afford their yearbook this year due to this. While in the large picture this isn't that big of a deal... it would still be nice for them to have a document of the good memories that happened this year. If you would like to purchase a yearbook to donate to a senior that cannot afford it this year, please contact Mr. Ogilvy at jogilvy@richmond.k12.mi.us. The yearbook sale ends on 4/24/20, if you are interested, please contact him before this. Thank you very much.

If you would like to purchase a yearbook to donate to a senior that cannot afford it this year, please contact Mr. Ogilvy at jogilvy@richmond.k12.mi.us. The yearbook sale ends on 4/24/20, if you are interested, please contact him before this. Thank you very much.

post_text:
A special shout out to the Food Service and redeployed "essential" Bus Drivers, Childcare, Paraprofessionals, and Preschool employees who prepared and distributed a total of 3,824 meal to 478 students!

Each meal package provided lunch for Thursday, breakfast and lunches for Friday, Saturday & Sunday, and breakfast on Monday. The need is great in our community and we are so proud of these employees for stepping up!

The next meal delivery and pick-up will take place on Monday, April 20, 2020. The Lee pick-up is open from 10-12:00pm.

PICK-UP MEAL OPTION: In addition, the District will have a drive-up/pick-up option, from 10:00AM until 12:00PM, for families to drive their vehicle through the bus loop at Will L. Lee Elementary School. District personnel will place all packaged meals in the vehicle or hand to parents or guardians as they drive through the bus loop. Families will not need to get out of their vehicles, but rather drive through and pickup.

This week in Mrs. Hunter's 2nd grade class, a Class Dojo video challenge was to create cereal box book reports. Students were asked to use a book they have recently read and to look into story elements, character traits, summaries and narrator of their story in order to create a cereal book report. Also, this week students detective skills were challenged to solve another math mystery (using time, addition/subtraction/fractions)- the case of the rotten eggs. Student practices summaries and editing sentences.
Olivia submitted a weather related question to WXYZ Kevin’s Questions and was selected! She asked how rainbows are created.
